snippet.textDisplay: Djokovic just has the misfortune of coming late to the party.  People had picked their favorites in the battle of fire v. ice and then along comes Djokovic who is better than both of them. As far as the criticism of his game, he plays very much like Chris Evert did in her heyday and she was appreciated for it although some called her boring.  The biggest differences are he serves better, moves faster, and he has the ability to hit the ball harder (relatively speaking).  In some ways when he is playing well he really is invincible.  And truthfully, the big 3 are not all that different from each other.  Their movement and bodies are but their styles of play and the style of play of most everybody today is basically the same.  I laugh to myself when everybody says Federer and Djokovic play completely different styles.  They are all power baseliners now with biggish serves and varying degrees of athleticism.  Gone are the days of real differences in the game of tennis.

snippet.textDisplay:
I'm Western European and like millions in Europe.....we support Novak Djokovic. He's also very popular in eastern Europe, Russia and Asia as a whole!
It doesn't really matter that he doesn't have as many fans as Nadal or Federer.....what matters are his personal achievements.

A lot of Federer's Grandslam titles were against 2nd tier players after the likes of Sampras, Agassi, Becker & Edberg retired. He beat people in Grandslam finals like Roddick, Safin, Phillppousos. Leyton Hewitt, Baghdatis, Fernando Gonzalez, Sodeling (his only French Open win in 2009).........none of these were great champion-like players by any stretch of the imagination. Roddick was probably the best of these Federer challengers at that time.....comparable to modern day Stan Warwrinka or maybe Andy Murray.
Nadal was only starting out and didn't really start challenging until 2005/6. ....and Novak Djokovic not until 2008 onwards.

Nadal was there throughout Federer's career.....though the argument against him being that GOAT is that 12 of his 19 grandslam titles were on slow clay courts of the French Open

By contrast Djovokic played his ENTIRE career during Nadal & Federer eras and during the pinnacles of their respective careers. He had to earn each and every one of his Grandslam titles against potentially the 2 of the greatest of all time. (even today, they are still challenging him for those GS titles!)

Since 2010....Djokovic has won 16 Grandslam titles, Nadal has won 13 GS and Federer won just 5 !!!!
Since 2010 Djokovic has definitely been the no.1 and the KINGPIN!

At the end of the day I can see Djokovic will eclipse both Federer and Nadal in terms of achievements....in terms of being No.1 for the most number of weeks, the most Grandslam titles, most Prize money won, most ATP finals, most ATP Tour Masters 1000 titles.

I can see Djokovic retiring around 35 or 36 yrs old, because of wanting to be more with his family. By then he would have eclipsed both Federer & Nadal in almost nearly all meaningful Tennis records.

People are fans of the Big 3 due to their personalties and their different playing styles.....as it should be.

Djokovic had the added handicap of being the last of the 3 to join the GOAT party......when many had already become fans of either Federer or Nadal.
It also doesn't help that he was born in Eastern Europe (Serbia)....because whether you like it or not geopolitical perceptions come into play. It's the same treatment you can witness by reading any Western mainstream media (or TV coverage) with regards to most the famous Russian sportsmen/ women (or Chinese)
Watch and you will see Danii Medevrev get the same treatment after all these 3 retire.

Thiem has a lot of holes in his game: inconsistent first serve (he couldn't put pressure on Djokovic from the start), hit the balls too flat and as a result have a lot of unforced errors, when at net he doesn't know what to do with the ball, bad overheads and on top of these he is mentally weak.
Personally I don't like Djokovic's game as he just steals points instead of creating them. The only player that can beat Djokovic in grand slams is Wawrinka who has the power and consistency to destroy Djokovic on any surface. Unfortunately, Wawrinka really disappointed me in the game with Zverev.
